<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n35272e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n35" href="#n35272e">N35 (VI.B.24)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n35all.htm#n35272e"> 272(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> exokionitii</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> <font color="green">[<i>History, Architecture and Antiquities</i>.&mdash;]</font> Hence the Arians, upon their expulsion from the city by Theodosius I., were allowed to hold their religious services in the Exokionion, seeing that it was an extra-mural district. This explains the fact that Arians are sometimes styled Exokionitae by ecclesiastical historians. <small> &ldquo;CONSTANTINOPLE&rdquo; <cite a>Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
